    <!-- ══ FORECAST ALGORITHM SECTION ════════════════════ -->
<section style="padding: var(--space-3xl) var(--space-xl);
                background: var(--surface);
                border-top: 1px solid var(--border);">
  <div style="max-width:1200px;margin:0 auto;">

    <div class="section-label">
      <i data-lucide="brain-circuit"
         style="width:14px;height:14px"></i>
      How It Works
    </div>

    <h2 class="section-title">
      How FCHAN Forecasts Your Harvest
    </h2>

    <p class="section-subtitle">
      FCHAN uses a scientifically proven agricultural method called
      <strong>Growing Degree Days (GDD)</strong> combined with
      real-time sensor data to predict when your crops will be ready.
    </p>

    <!-- Step cards -->
    <div style="display:grid;
                grid-template-columns:repeat(auto-fill,minmax(280px,1fr));
                gap:var(--space-lg);
                margin-bottom:var(--space-2xl);">

      <div style="background:var(--bg);border:1px solid var(--border);
                  border-radius:var(--radius-md);padding:var(--space-xl);
                  border-top:4px solid var(--primary);">
        <div style="font-size:32px;margin-bottom:var(--space-md);"></div>
        <h4 style="margin-bottom:var(--space-sm);">Step 1 — Heat Accumulation</h4>
        <p style="font-size:var(--text-sm);">
          Plants don't grow by calendar days — they grow by
          <strong>accumulated heat</strong>. Each day we calculate:
          <br><br>
          <code style="background:var(--surface-2);padding:4px 8px;
                        border-radius:4px;font-size:12px;">
            GDD = ((Max°C + Min°C) / 2) − Base°C
          </code>
          <br><br>
          A tomato (base 10°C) on a day where max=28°C and min=16°C
          accumulates <strong>12 GDD</strong>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div style="background:var(--bg);border:1px solid var(--border);
                  border-radius:var(--radius-md);padding:var(--space-xl);
                  border-top:4px solid var(--info);">
        <div style="font-size:32px;margin-bottom:var(--space-md);"></div>
        <h4 style="margin-bottom:var(--space-sm);">Step 2 — Progress Tracking</h4>
        <p style="font-size:var(--text-sm);">
          Each plant species needs a total GDD to reach harvest.
          For example, tomatoes need ~1000 GDD.
          <br><br>
          <code style="background:var(--surface-2);padding:4px 8px;
                        border-radius:4px;font-size:12px;">
            Progress = Accumulated GDD / Total GDD × 100%
          </code>
          <br><br>
          At 450 GDD accumulated → plant is at <strong>45%</strong> growth.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div style="background:var(--bg);border:1px solid var(--border);
                  border-radius:var(--radius-md);padding:var(--space-xl);
                  border-top:4px solid var(--warning);">
        <div style="font-size:32px;margin-bottom:var(--space-md);"></div>
        <h4 style="margin-bottom:var(--space-sm);">Step 3 — Soil Adjustment</h4>
        <p style="font-size:var(--text-sm);">
          Soil moisture affects growth speed. If soil is too dry
          or too wet, a <strong>penalty factor</strong> slows
          the effective growth rate:
          <br><br>
          <code style="background:var(--surface-2);padding:4px 8px;
                        border-radius:4px;font-size:12px;">
            Effective GDD = Daily GDD × Moisture Factor
          </code>
          <br><br>
          Optimal moisture (60–80%) → factor = 1.0 (full speed).
          Dry soil (&lt;40%) → factor = 0.6 (60% speed).
        </p>
      </div>

      <div style="background:var(--bg);border:1px solid var(--border);
                  border-radius:var(--radius-md);padding:var(--space-xl);
                  border-top:4px solid var(--success);">
        <div style="font-size:32px;margin-bottom:var(--space-md);"></div>
        <h4 style="margin-bottom:var(--space-sm);">Step 4 — Harvest Date</h4>
        <p style="font-size:var(--text-sm);">
          Using the remaining GDD needed and the daily average,
          we estimate the harvest date:
          <br><br>
          <code style="background:var(--surface-2);padding:4px 8px;
                        border-radius:4px;font-size:12px;">
            Days left = Remaining GDD / Effective daily GDD
          </code>
          <br><br>
          Today + days left = <strong>Estimated harvest date</strong>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div style="background:var(--bg);border:1px solid var(--border);
                  border-radius:var(--radius-md);padding:var(--space-xl);
                  border-top:4px solid #9b59b6;">
        <div style="font-size:32px;margin-bottom:var(--space-md);"></div>
        <h4 style="margin-bottom:var(--space-sm);">Step 5 — Health Score</h4>
        <p style="font-size:var(--text-sm);">
          A 0–100 score based on how close all sensor readings
          are to the optimal range for that plant species:
          <br><br>
          Temperature, humidity, soil pH, moisture and light
          are each scored and averaged.
          <br><br>
          <strong>85–100</strong> = Excellent &nbsp;
          <strong>50–70</strong> = Fair &nbsp;
          <strong>&lt;30</strong> = Critical
        </p>
      </div>

      <div style="background:linear-gradient(135deg,var(--secondary),var(--primary));
                  border-radius:var(--radius-md);padding:var(--space-xl);
                  color:white;">
        <div style="font-size:32px;margin-bottom:var(--space-md);"></div>
        <h4 style="color:white;margin-bottom:var(--space-sm);">
          Scientific Basis
        </h4>
        <p style="font-size:var(--text-sm);color:rgba(255,255,255,0.85);">
          The GDD method was developed in the 19th century and
          is still used by agricultural scientists worldwide.
          Plant base temperatures and GDD requirements come from
          USDA crop guides and university research.
          <br><br>
          FCHAN combines this proven science with real IoT sensor
          data for accurate, personalized forecasts.
        </p>
      </div>

    </div>

    <!-- Simple visual formula summary -->
    <div style="background:linear-gradient(135deg,
                  rgba(26,82,118,0.05),rgba(39,174,96,0.05));
                border:1px solid var(--border);
                border-radius:var(--radius-lg);
                padding:var(--space-2xl);
                text-align:center;">
      <h3 style="margin-bottom:var(--space-lg);">
        The Complete Formula
      </h3>
      <div style="display:flex;align-items:center;
                  justify-content:center;flex-wrap:wrap;
                  gap:var(--space-md);font-size:var(--text-sm);">
        <div style="background:var(--surface);border:1px solid var(--border);
                    border-radius:var(--radius-sm);padding:var(--space-md)
                    var(--space-lg);font-weight:600;">
          Temperature History
        </div>
        <span style="color:var(--text-muted);font-size:20px;">+</span>
        <div style="background:var(--surface);border:1px solid var(--border);
                    border-radius:var(--radius-sm);padding:var(--space-md)
                    var(--space-lg);font-weight:600;">
          Soil Moisture
        </div>
        <span style="color:var(--text-muted);font-size:20px;">+</span>
        <div style="background:var(--surface);border:1px solid var(--border);
                    border-radius:var(--radius-sm);padding:var(--space-md)
                    var(--space-lg);font-weight:600;">
          Plant Species Data
        </div>
        <span style="color:var(--primary);font-size:24px;font-weight:800;">
          =
        </span>
        <div style="background:linear-gradient(135deg,var(--primary),var(--secondary));
                    color:white;border-radius:var(--radius-sm);
                    padding:var(--space-md) var(--space-lg);font-weight:700;">
          Harvest Date Forecast
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

  </div>
</section>

    <!-- ══ FOOTER ═════════════════════════════════════ -->
